{"cursor":"2926","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Edmond Albius' (1829 â 9 August 1880) was an important figure in the\ncultivation of vanilla. At the age of 12, he invented a technique for\npollinating vanilla orchids quickly and profitably. Albius's technique\nrevolutionized the cultivation of vanilla and made it possible to profitably\ngrow vanilla beans away from their native Mexico.\n\nAlbius was born in St. Suzanne, RÃ©union. His mother, a slave, died during his\nbirth, and he was adopted by her master, FÃ©rÃ©ol Bellier Beaumont.\n\nFrench colonists brought vanilla beans to RÃ©union (and nearby Mauritius) in the\n1820s with the hope of starting production there. However, the vines were\nsterile because no insect would pollinate them. In the 1830s, Charles Morren, a\nprofessor of botany at the University of LiÃ¨ge in Belgium, developed a method of\nhand-pollinating vanilla, but his technique was slow and required too much\neffort to make cultivating vanilla a moneymaking proposition. Hazen J (1995)\nVanilla. Chronicle Books. San Francisco, CA.\n\nIn 1841, Albius discovered how to quickly pollinate the vanilla orchid with a\nthin stick or blade of grass and a simple thumb gesture. With the stick or grass\nblade, field hands lift the rostellum, the flap that separates the male anther\nfrom the female stigma, and then, with their thumbs, smear the sticky pollen\nfrom the anther over the stigma.\n\nAlbiusâs manual pollination method is still used today, as nearly all vanilla is\npollinated by hand. After Albiusâs discovery, RÃ©union became for a time the\nworld's largest supplier of vanilla. French colonists used Albius's technique in\nMadagascar to cultivate vanilla, and Madagascar remains the world's chief\nvanilla producer. Rain P (1986) The Vanilla Cookbook. Celestial Arts.\nBerkeley, CA.\n\nIn 1848, France outlawed slavery in its colonies, and Albius left the plantation\nfor St. Denis, where he worked as a kitchen servant. He was convicted of\nstealing jewellery and sentenced to ten years in prison, but the sentence was\ncommuted after five years when the governor granted him clemency in light of his\nenormous contribution to vanilla production in RÃ©union. Albius died in poverty\nin St. Suzanne in 1880. \n","linknr":103,"url":"Edmond_Albius","recorded":1364033712,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Edmond_Albius&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Edmond_Albius&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Edmond_Albius.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Edmond_Albius.jpg/250px-Edmond_Albius.jpg","/wiki/File:Edmond_Albius.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Vanilla","/wiki/Mexico","/wiki/Sainte-Suzanne,_R%C3%A9union","/wiki/R%C3%A9union","/wiki/Mauritius","/wiki/Charles_Fran%C3%A7ois_Antoine_Morren","/wiki/Belgium","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Rostellum","/wiki/Anther","/wiki/Gynoecium#The_stigma_and_style","/wiki/Pollen","/wiki/Madagascar","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Plantation","/wiki/Saint-Denis,_R%C3%A9union","/wiki/Sainte-Suzanne,_R%C3%A9union","/w/index.php?title=Edmond_Albius&action=edit&section=1","#cite_ref-1","#cite_ref-2","/wiki/Wikipedia:Persondata"